<ns3036:section xmlns:ns3036="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2se.security.jaas.subjectsPrincipalsAndCredentials">
    
    <ns3037:title xmlns:ns3037="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Subjects, Principals and Credentials</ns3037:title>

<ns3038:para xmlns:ns3038="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">A <ns3039:emphasis xmlns:ns3039="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"> Subject</ns3039:emphasis> is an external object which typically needs to be authenticated.
It may represent a user or another system. Once the subject has been
authenticated, it is populated with principals.</ns3038:para>

<ns3040:para xmlns:ns3040="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns3041:emphasis xmlns:ns3041="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"> Principals</ns3041:emphasis> represent aspects which may be used to identify a subject. For
example, the name (<ns3042:abbrev xmlns:ns3042="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">e.g.</ns3042:abbrev> Jill Jones), an identity number and a passport number
may 3 different associated identities or principals for a particular subject.</ns3040:para>

<ns3043:para xmlns:ns3043="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">A subject may own a number of security-related attributes called 
<ns3044:emphasis xmlns:ns3044="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"> credentials</ns3044:emphasis>. These credentials may be any objects. JAAS distinguishes 
between <ns3045:emphasis xmlns:ns3045="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"> public credentials</ns3045:emphasis> and <ns3046:emphasis xmlns:ns3046="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"> private credentials</ns3046:emphasis>.</ns3043:para>

<ns3047:para xmlns:ns3047="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns3048:emphasis xmlns:ns3048="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"> Public credentials</ns3048:emphasis> are often publicly known and  distributed. They may  
represent user names or public keys. </ns3047:para>

<ns3049:para xmlns:ns3049="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns3050:emphasis xmlns:ns3050="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"> Private credentials</ns3050:emphasis> represent sensitive credentials which that need to
be protected from public access. Examples of private credentials are passwords
and private keys.</ns3049:para>
    
</ns3036:section>